"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63562","Cabinet Office","false","2014-06-30","<p>There is on-going work assessing and mitigating vulnerabilities in UK's critical national infrastructure. Details of this work, including any assessments, are classified.</p><p>Progress against the National Cyber Security Strategy is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/uk-cyber-security-strategy-statement-on-progress-2-years-on" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/uk-cyber-security-strategy-statement-on-progress-2-years-on</a></p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-06-30T16:32:51.3285009Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63562/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63562/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-06-24","Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many assessments of (a) nuclear facilities and (b) other critical infrastructure have been undertaken against his Department's information assurance maturity model; and if he will publish all such assessments undertaken since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","202073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63563","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-30","<p>The National Audit Office (NAO) have conducted two value for money assessments on the private finance initiative contract between HM Revenue and Customs and Mapeley STEPS Contractor Limited. The first of these, PFI: The STEPS Deal, was published by the NAO on 7 May 2004. The second NAO value for money assessment, HM Revenue &amp; Customs' Estate Private Finance Deal Eight Years On, was published on 3 December 2009.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-06-30T14:04:42.2626685Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63563/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63563/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-24","Mapeley","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when assessments have been made of the value for money of the private finance initiative contract between HM Revenue and Customs and Mapeley Steps Contractor Limited; and when the first such assessment was made.","false","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","202079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63564","HM Treasury","false","2014-07-03","<p>The 2013-14 appraisal data is not available yet.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-07-03T15:45:36.1716155Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63564/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63564/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-24","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of (a) disabled and (b) all other staff employed by his Department received each level of performance rating in their end of year performance assessment for 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","202064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63565","HM Treasury","false","2014-07-01","<p>Since January 2011, central government departments have been required to publish on Contracts Finder information on the contracts they award (www.contractsfinder.businesslink.gov.uk/). In addition, departments publish details of spend in excess of £25,000.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury and its executive agencies and non-departmental public bodies do not hold any current contracts with the Educational Testing Service or any of that organisation's subsidiaries.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2014-07-01T14:35:58.774467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63565/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63565/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-24","Educational Testing Service","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what current contracts (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's executive agencies or non-departmental public bodies hold with the Educational Testing Service or any of that organisation's subsidiaries.","false","Biography information for Nick Gibb","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","202176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63566","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-30","<p>No such assessment has been made. There is no single rate of tourism VAT. The VAT rate paid on goods and services bought by tourists in the UK is exactly the same as that which applies to UK residents. This means for example, that tourists can benefit from the UK's zero rates of VAT on certain foods, children's clothing and certain transport. But it also means they are charged VAT on things like catering services (the supply of meals, alcohol, snacks and drinks) sold by restaurants, pubs, cafes and canteens.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-06-30T14:44:42.9636598Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63566/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63566/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-24","Tourism: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of cutting the rate of tourism VAT on the tourism balance of payments.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","202041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63567","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-30","<p>The Government takes the enforcement of national minimum wage (NMW) very seriously and HMRC enforce the NMW legislation on behalf of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS). It does that by investigating all complaints made about employers suspected of not paying the minimum wage, in addition, carrying out targeted enforcement where it identifies a high risk of non-payment of NMW across the whole of the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The National Minimum Wage team in Northern Ireland contains six full-time and two-part-time staff with all using Belfast as a base location.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, as I explained in my previous response, HMRC deploys resources to risk, so work relating to a specific geographical area may not always be undertaken by the NMW team based in that area. In addition, the NMW Dynamic Response Team (DRT) provides a multi-agency response to emerging risks, high profile casework and compliance initiatives across the UK.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","202256","2014-06-30T14:00:27.8330395Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63567/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63567/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-24","Minimum Wage: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 23 June 2014, Official Report, column 36W, on minimum wage: Northern Ireland, whether HM Revenue and Customs' national minimum wage enforcement team have any staff located in Northern Ireland outside the city of Belfast.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","202044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63568","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-30","<p>VAT receipts from the sale of sanitary products, subject to the reduced rate of VAT, are estimated to have been approximately £15m in each of the last five years.</p><p>VAT rules apply the standard rate of 20 per cent to most goods and services. While there are exceptions to this standard rate, these are strictly limited under EU VAT law.</p><p>One such exception is that female sanitary products can be subject to a reduced rate of VAT. Since 2001, the UK has therefore applied a 5 per cent reduced rate of VAT, the lowest permissible under EU law, to the supply of sanitary products.</p><p> </p><p>The application of VAT in the EU, including rates and flexibilities afforded to member states in this regard, is governed by EU law. It means, for example that the Government cannot apply a zero rate tofemale sanitary products. That would require a change to EU VAT legislation, which would require a proposal from the European Commission and the unanimous agreement of all 28 member states.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-06-30T14:26:53.3314452Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63568/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63568/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-24","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has accrued to the Exchequer in VAT receipts from the sale of sanitary products in each of the last five years; and if he will review the applicability of such a tax with existing equality legislation.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","202135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63569","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-30","<p>16th June 2014, Official Report, column 395W does not relate to discussions between HM Revenue and Customs, Mapeley and Network Rail. Representatives from HMRC Estates and Support Services Team and from local HMRC business attended initial discussions with Mapeley and Network Rail on proposals for the construction of a multi storey car park on land adjacent to Priory Court Dover. Previous replies have explained that further discussions, on the sale of land on the western perimeter of the Priory Court site, have been between Mapeley as the freehold owner of Priory Court and Network Rail.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2014-06-30T14:29:35.2220205Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63569/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63569/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-24","Dover Priory Station","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 16 June 2014, Official Report, column 395W, on Revenue and Customs, which personnel attended discussions between HM Revenue and Customs, Mapeley and Network Rail regarding the sale of land on the western perimeter of the Priory Court site.","false","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","202196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63570","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-30","<p>The Government's response to the consultation on design and operation of Tax-Free Childcare set out in paragraph 6.11 that the Government will provide detailed online information and consider other communications channels that can be used to raise awareness and understanding of Tax-Free Childcare.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government will work with stakeholders, including parents, to develop guidance to help parents understand the scheme, including the interactions between Tax-Free Childcare and other Government support.</p>","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan",,"2014-06-30T13:45:18.8193497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63570/answer","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63570/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-24","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 6.10 of Delivering Tax-free childcare: the Government's response to the consultation on design and operation published in March 2014, what clear guidance and communications tools his Department plans to provide to help parents make informed decisions on which scheme is best for their circumstances.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","202254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63571","HM Treasury","false","2014-06-30","<p>The Government takes the enforcement of national minimum wage (NMW) very seriously and HMRC enforce the NMW legislation on behalf of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS). It does that by investigating all complaints made about employers suspected of not paying the minimum wage, in addition, carrying out targeted enforcement where it identifies a high risk of non-payment of NMW across the whole of the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The National Minimum Wage team in Northern Ireland contains six full-time and two-part-time staff with all using Belfast as a base location.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, as I explained in my previous response, HMRC deploys resources to risk, so work relating to a specific geographical area may not always be undertaken by the NMW team based in that area. In addition, the NMW Dynamic Response Team (DRT) provides a multi-agency response to emerging risks, high profile casework and compliance initiatives across the UK.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","202044","2014-06-30T14:00:27.9268149Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63571/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63571/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-06-24","Minimum Wage: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 23 June 2014, Official Report, column 36W, on minimum wage: Northern Ireland, how many people are employed (a) full-time and (b) part-time in the HM Revenue and Customs national minimum wage enforcement team based in Belfast.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","202256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63572","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>None.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-06-30T15:32:49.7739118Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63572/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63572/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-24","Educational Testing Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what contracts (a) his Department and (b) its agencies and non-departmental public bodies holds with the Educational Testing Service or its subsidiaries.","false","Biography information for Nick Gibb","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","202241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63573","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>The National Planning Policy Framework and our planning guidance make clear that Local Plans should be supported by evidence to establish what level of infrastructure is needed to enable the development proposed for the area and how it will be delivered.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At examination, local authorities should justify their plan policies, including their deliverability over the plan period. Where an inspector concludes that there are fundamental issues regarding the soundness of the Plan, they will identify any conflicts between a draft local plan and national policy and regulatory process. They are able to recommend modifications to overcome these issues if they are asked to do so by the council itself.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-06-30T15:42:19.0968318Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63573/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63573/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-24","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance he gives local authorities on assessing the infrastructure required for sites which are included in their site allocations process; and what steps he takes if local authorities do not adhere to that guidance.","false","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew","202253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63575","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>My Department has not made its own estimate of the average lettings agency fees charged to tenants in the private rented sector but has taken note of the figures reported by independent organisations, such as the Office of Fair Trading, Shelter and Which.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is currently legislating through the Consumer Rights Bill to ensure there is full transparency on fees charged by all letting agencies, ending hidden fees.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>By contrast, I would observe that the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors (RICS) has commented that the policy proposals of HM Opposition on fees would harm tenants, as it would lead to: “increases in rents to cover the additional costs visited upon landlords” and a “reduction in supply” (RICS,<em> Letting agent fees for tenants: a tale of two amendments</em>, 15 May 2014).</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-06-30T15:16:07.301251Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63575/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63575/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-24","Letting Agents: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the average lettings agency fees charged to tenants in the private rented sector (a) at the start of a new tenancy and (b) when a tenancy is renewed.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","202249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63577","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-03","<p>Yes.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-07-03T15:29:46.1569523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63577/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63577/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-24","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether a local planning authority which rejects a housing development application which is subsequently approved on appeal by the Planning Inspectorate are still eligible for the New Homes Bonus.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","202127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63578","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>The levels of crewing available for each authority, whether or not during periods of strike action, are dependent upon a number of factors. These include the duty system being worked locally, availability of on-call firefighters and, during strike periods, local contingency arrangements, which are the responsibility of each fire and rescue authority. The Department collects details of appliance availability from local fire and rescue authorities on a confidential basis. The arrangements for business continuity planning during strike action are kept under review by the Chief Fire and Rescue Adviser.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The principles of the recall to duty protocol, published as National Joint Council for Fire and Rescue Services Circular NJC/09/13, were agreed between the Chief Fire and Rescue Adviser, the Fire Brigades Union and the National Employers. Appendix 1 applies to fire and rescue authorities in England and makes clear that the Chief Fire Officers are responsible for arrangements locally, in accordance with their service's major incident policies. I am confident that should there be a major disaster, striking firefighters would return to work.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","202132 ; 202133","2014-06-30T15:30:32.3302391Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63578/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63578/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-24","Fire Services: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish his assessment of the workability of the protocol agreed between his Department and the Fire Brigades Union on recall to duty in the event of a major incident or national disaster.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","202134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63579","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-01","<p> </p><p>Grant applicants submitting bids to the Coastal Communities Fund are expected to demonstrate the need for their project, which can include levels of poverty and deprivation in their area. This information is one of a range of factors that are taken into account in the assessment of grant applications. However, the Fund is not specifically targeted on deprived coastal towns. Its aim is to support jobs and growth in coastal communities across the United Kingdom where projects can best exploit local assets and opportunities to unlock their growth potential. In addition to demonstrating need, applications to the Fund must be clearly linked to an economic opportunity to create and safeguard jobs within the coastal community. Coastal flooding and erosion risk management and repair are also priorities for grant aid where proposed works support economic development.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2014-07-01T15:39:45.4202305Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63579/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63579/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-24","Coastal Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether levels of poverty and deprivation in coastal towns are considered by his Department when making grants from the Coastal Communities Fund.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","202072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63580","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-01","<p> </p><p>The Coastal Communities Fund supports economic growth and jobs in coastal communities across the United Kingdom. We have awarded a total of 104 grants under the Fund to date in England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland at a total value of £53.6 million. A table has been placed in the Library of the House giving the details requested for all 104 grants.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Decisions on grant awards in England are taken by Government Ministers. In Wales and Northern Ireland grant awards are taken by panels involving officials from the BIG Lottery Fund and Devolved Administrations, and in Scotland by independently appointed panels.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-07-01T15:36:33.0028031Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63580/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63580/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-24","Coastal Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what grants have been given by the Coastal Communities Fund to date; which town, county and parliamentary constituency received each such grant; and what the size and purpose of each grant was.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","202076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63581","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-09-03","<p> </p><p>The table below provides a summary of the performance results for non-Senior Civil Service staff for whom the DCLG process applied, where disability has been declared, and whose performance markings have been entered into the HR database:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em>Number of staff</em></p></td><td><p><em>Exceptional</em></p></td><td><p><em>Good</em></p></td><td><p><em>Development</em></p><p><em>Needed</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Not Disabled</p></td><td><p>217</p></td><td><p>824</p></td><td><p>94</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Disabled</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>45</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Due to changes in methodology in the manner in which such assessments are undertaken, these figures are not comparative with those given to the hon. Member in the answer to her of 4 November 2013, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 22W.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The small sample sizes may mean the results are not statistically significant. We will be undertaking further analysis of the wider performance outcomes across both performance years and all protected characteristics. We will consider whether action is required to address any clear findings.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department provides a reasonable adjustments service, which has recently been subject to a review, to allow staff to ensure that a person with a disability is not put at a substantial disadvantage compared to non-disabled persons generally, who work under the same conditions. The Department’s Disability Champion also continues to work closely with the Disability Staff Network in raising awareness of disability issues to the wider Department.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-09-03T14:19:51.8178943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63581/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63581/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-24","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of (a) disabled and (b) all other staff employed by his Department received each level of performance rating in their end of year performance assessment for 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","202050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63582","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-03","<p> </p><p>Inappropriately sited wind turbines can cause significant harm to the local environment. Hence, last year, we changed planning guidance to strengthen the protection of landscape and heritage in relation to onshore wind.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Looking forward, we are keeping planning policy on renewable energy under review and will consider whether any further steps are appropriate in the light of this monitoring. We are open to representations.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2014-07-03T15:16:47.7003744Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63582/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63582/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-06-24","Wind Power: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will amend paragraph 98 of the National Planning Policy Framework to require applicants for onshore wind energy developments to demonstrate an overall national need for renewable energy.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","202034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63583","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-18","<p>As part of our Local TV licencing programme, Ofcom advertised the following locations with a deadline of 7 January 2014: Barnstaple, Basingstoke, Derry/Londonderry, Gloucester, Guildford, Limavady, Luton, Maidstone, Plymouth, Reading and Salisbury and Ofcom is in the process of considering the resulting applications. Out of these locations, Ofcom only received applications for five: Reading, Basingstoke, Guildford, Salisbury and Maidstone. The licences for Reading, Salisbury and Guildford have been awarded by Ofcom (on 3 June 2014) and Ofcom expects to be able to make a decision on the remaining two locations, namely Basingstoke and Maidstone shortly.</p><p>Ofcom plans to invite applications for further areas later this year.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-18T11:07:17.9165276Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63583/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63583/answer","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63583/answer/previousversion/7067","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-24","Local Broadcasting: Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has for the issuing of further licences for local television.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","202202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63584","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-02","<p>DCMS holds no records on the number or location of memorials to commemorate the war dead. Information about war memorials throughout the UK is held by both the Imperial War Museum and the War Memorials Trust. The Imperial War Museum is working with its partners to make this information more easily accessible to the public.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-02T08:23:42.4590009Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63584/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63584/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-24","War Memorials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what information his Department holds on the (a) number and (b) location of memorials to commemorate the war dead in the (i) First World War and (ii) Second World War; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63585","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-01","<p>The table sets out the percentage of employees, within each performance category, who have declared a disability, and the percentage of all other staff in each performance category for the 2013-14 reporting year for assessments received to date. The percentage of all other staff includes staff who have either explicitly declared that they do not have a disability, have chosen the ‘prefer not to say' option, or have not responded to the question at all.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Percentage</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Excellent </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Good</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Must Improve</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Percentage of employees who have declared a disability in each performance rating</p></td><td><p><strong>1%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>4%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Percentage of all other staff employed in each performance rating</p></td><td><p><strong>35%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>58%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) takes seriously its obligations to collect diversity data as required by the Equality Act 2010. All staff have been asked to provide personal diversity data to be held anonymously, and we continue to encourage increased declaration by staff. As such these figures will not be fully representative of workforce diversity.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-07-01T16:48:32.7248894Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63585/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63585/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-24","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of (a) disabled and (b) all other staff employed by his Department received each level of performance rating in their end of year performance assessment for 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","202051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63586","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-02","<p>The DCMS-run Memorial Grant Scheme has a budget of £543,000 for this financial year. Grants are available to charities and faith groups, and can be used to repair and maintain war memorials. The Government has today announced that it will give the War Memorials Trust up to £3 million over the First World War centenary period to boost the funds available to local communities for the repair and conservation of war memorials. English Heritage, Imperial War Museums and Civic Voice will together be given £1.5 million over the same period to deliver better protection through Listing, a greater pool of specialist skills, a national register of war memorials, and a network of trained volunteers.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-02T08:22:16.910325Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63586/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63586/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-24","War Memorials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what funding his Department has allocated to the maintenance of war memorials in each of the next three years; what steps it takes to ensure that war memorials are maintained to a high standard; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63587","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p>Following the very successful commemorations to mark the 70th anniversary of D-Day we will now be focusing in more detail across Government on how the 70th anniversary of the end of the Second World War in 2015 might be marked in an appropriate manner. I expect an announcement to be made later in the year.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","202025 ; 202026 ; 202178 ; 202179","2014-07-02T15:31:34.0065692Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63587/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63587/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","World War II: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much funding has been allocated for commemorations of the 70th anniversary of the end of the Second World War; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63588","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p>Following the very successful commemorations to mark the 70th anniversary of D-Day we will now be focusing in more detail across Government on how the 70th anniversary of the end of the Second World War in 2015 might be marked in an appropriate manner. I expect an announcement to be made later in the year.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","202025 ; 202026 ; 202179 ; 202185","2014-07-02T15:31:33.798803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63588/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63588/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","World War II: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many officials in his Department are engaged (a) full-time and (b) part-time in preparations to commemorate the 70th anniversary of the end of the Second World War; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63589","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p>Following the very successful commemorations to mark the 70th anniversary of D-Day we will now be focusing in more detail across Government on how the 70th anniversary of the end of the Second World War in 2015 might be marked in an appropriate manner. I expect an announcement to be made later in the year.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","202025 ; 202026 ; 202178 ; 202185","2014-07-02T15:31:33.9081827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63589/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63589/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63589/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","World War II: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make it his policy to apply a motif on all his Department's commemorative items and events associated with the 70th anniversary of the end of the Second World War; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63590","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-01","<p>The Department does not hold any contracts with the Educational Testing Service or any of its subsidiaries. We do not hold information centrally on our executive agency or non-departmental public bodies.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-07-01T16:49:35.2178683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63590/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63590/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63590/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-24","Educational Testing Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what current contracts (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's executive agencies or non-departmental public bodies hold with the Educational Testing Service or any of that organisation's subsidiaries.","false","Biography information for Nick Gibb","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","202166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63591","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-01","<p>Following the 2010 public consultation on options for the management of the wreck site of HMS Victory 1744 it was decided to place responsibility for the future management of the site on a charitable trust. The Maritime Heritage Foundation (MHF) was a newly formed charity and its objectives ‘to recover, preserve and display in public museums, to promote knowledge and understanding of our maritime heritage through educational projects' were considered to be well suited for the management of the wreck site. No additional checks were made because the MHF is a registered charity under the auspices of the Charity Commission and subject to its rules and regulations.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-01T16:58:11.1945535Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63591/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63591/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-24","HMS Victory","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what background checks his Department undertook on Lord Lingfield's charitable foundation before the transfer of the wreck of HMS Victory 1744.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","202042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63592","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-17","<p>As the centenary of the outbreak of the First World War approaches, it is right that we acknowledge the important work undertaken by the Commonwealth War Graves Commission (CWGC) to commemorate those who gave their lives during both World Wars. <br><br>The CWGC receives financial contributions from its member nations based on the number of graves it maintains on behalf of each nation. Accordingly the UK Government contributes 78.43% to the total CWGC funding. <br><br>Financial records are retained for seven years. Information held by the Ministry of Defence indicates that over the last seven financial years the UK Government has made the following payments to CWGC for the maintenance of graves of those who died during the First and Second World Wars. The figures include UK VAT: <br><br>2007-08 – £34,799,000<br>2008-09 – £35,153,000<br>2009-10 – £46,545,000 <br>2010-11 – £43,341,000<br>2011-12 – £46,288,000<br>2012-13 – £44,636,487<br>2013-14 – £47,318,041<br><br>With regard to future funding, the UK will continue to meet its obligation to pay the appropriate percentage (currently 78.43%) of the total CWGC funding. <br><br>The Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport is discussing with the CWGC the scope for enhancing information and interpretation at burial sites as part of the centenary commemorations.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","202186","2014-07-17T16:01:52.1865752Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63592/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63592/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63592/answer/previousversion/7750","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","War Graves","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department (a) spent in each of the last 10 years and (b) plans to spend in each of the next three years on maintaining war graves; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63593","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-01","<p>DCMS has spent the following amounts in each of the last 10 years maintaining national memorials:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Spend (£)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>529,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>269,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>334,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>229,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>230,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>391,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>854,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>714,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>130,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004/05</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The DCMS-run Memorial Grant Scheme has a budget of £543,000 for this financial year. Grants are available to charities and faith groups, and can be used to repair and maintain war memorials. The Government has today announced that it will give the War Memorials Trust up to £3 million over the First World War centenary period to boost the funds available to local communities for the repair and conservation of war memorials. English Heritage, Imperial War Museums and Civic Voice will together be given £1.5 million over the same period to deliver better protection through Listing, a greater pool of specialist skills, a national register of war memorials, and a network of trained volunteers.</p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-07-01T16:51:20.3258885Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63593/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63593/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-24","Monuments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department (a) spent in each of the last 10 years and (b) plans to spend in each of the next three years on maintaining national memorials; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63594","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-01","<p>DCMS has given the amounts set out from the Memorial Grant Scheme in each of the last 10 years:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Funding MGS (£)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>529,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>269,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>334,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>229,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>230,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008/09</p></td><td><p>391,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007/08</p></td><td><p>854,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006/07</p></td><td><p>714,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005/06</p></td><td><p>130,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004/05</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-07-01T16:52:55.2391496Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63594/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63594/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-24","Memorials Grant Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department gave to the Memorials Grant Scheme in each of the last 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63595","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p>Following the very successful commemorations to mark the 70th anniversary of D-Day we will now be focusing in more detail across Government on how the 70th anniversary of the end of the Second World War in 2015 might be marked in an appropriate manner. I expect an announcement to be made later in the year.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","202026 ; 202178 ; 202179 ; 202185","2014-07-02T15:31:33.6112859Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63595/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63595/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","War Graves and Memorials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will provide funding to refurbish war graves and war memorials (a) in the UK and (b) overseas as part of the commemoration of the 70th anniversary of the ending of the Second World War; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63596","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p>Following the very successful commemorations to mark the 70th anniversary of D-Day we will now be focusing in more detail across Government on how the 70th anniversary of the end of the Second World War in 2015 might be marked in an appropriate manner. I expect an announcement to be made later in the year.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","202025 ; 202178 ; 202179 ; 202185","2014-07-02T15:31:33.7050495Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63596/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63596/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63596/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","World War II: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with which countries his Department has (a) held discussions and (b) plans to hold discussions on (i) joint events and (ii) a UK presence at overseas events to commemorate the 70th anniversary of the ending of the Second World War; when any such discussions (A) took place and (B) are due to take place; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63597","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-02","<p>None. DCMS has no responsibility for cemeteries.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-02T08:20:34.3176732Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63597/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63597/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-06-24","Cemeteries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent representations he has received on the establishment of a national cemetery; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63598","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-30","<p>The Ministry of Defence, including Executive Agencies and Non-Departmental Public Bodies, does not currently have any contracts with the Educational Testing Service or its subsidiary companies.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-30T13:36:07.137269Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63598/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63598/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","Educational Testing Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what current contracts (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's executive agencies or non-departmental public bodies hold with the Educational Testing Service or any of that organisation's subsidiaries.","false","Biography information for Nick Gibb","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","202167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63599","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="8"> </td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="5"> </td><td colspan="6" rowspan="5">The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","199300","2014-06-30T13:42:15.7183156Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63599/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63599/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","Army: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many British armed forces personnel were operationally deployed to Northern Ireland in each year from April 1984 to April 2010; and how many such personnel were accompanied by a (a) spouse or (b) civil partner in each such year.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","202093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63600","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-30","<p>This information is not yet available.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-06-30T13:38:11.1980552Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63600/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63600/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of (a) disabled and (b) all other staff employed by his Department received each level of performance rating in their end of year performance assessment for 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","202052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63601","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-17","<p>As the centenary of the outbreak of the First World War approaches, it is right that we acknowledge the important work undertaken by the Commonwealth War Graves Commission (CWGC) to commemorate those who gave their lives during both World Wars. <br><br>The CWGC receives financial contributions from its member nations based on the number of graves it maintains on behalf of each nation. Accordingly the UK Government contributes 78.43% to the total CWGC funding. <br><br>Financial records are retained for seven years. Information held by the Ministry of Defence indicates that over the last seven financial years the UK Government has made the following payments to CWGC for the maintenance of graves of those who died during the First and Second World Wars. The figures include UK VAT: <br><br>2007-08 – £34,799,000<br>2008-09 – £35,153,000<br>2009-10 – £46,545,000 <br>2010-11 – £43,341,000<br>2011-12 – £46,288,000<br>2012-13 – £44,636,487<br>2013-14 – £47,318,041<br><br>With regard to future funding, the UK will continue to meet its obligation to pay the appropriate percentage (currently 78.43%) of the total CWGC funding. <br><br>The Department for Culture, Media &amp; Sport is discussing with the CWGC the scope for enhancing information and interpretation at burial sites as part of the centenary commemorations.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","202022","2014-07-17T16:01:52.077172Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63601/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63601/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63601/answer/previousversion/7749","Biography information for Anna Soubry","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","War Graves","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department (a) has given in each of the last 10 years and (b) plans to give in the next three years to the Commonwealth War Graves Commission to (i) mark and (ii) maintain the graves of those who died during the World Wars; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63602","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p>The Royal Scots Dragoon Guards (Royal Scots DG) and 2 Close Support Battalion Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers (2 CS Bn REME) are due to relocate to RAF Leuchars during the summer of 2015, whilst 110 Provost Company (110 Pro Coy), Royal Military Police, will arrive in tranches from late 2015 to 2018. <br><br>The number of personnel, spouses and school aged children are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td>UNIT</td><td>Personnel</td><td>Spouses</td><td>Children(0-4)</td><td>Children(5-16)</td></tr><tr><td>Royal Scots DG</td><td>404</td><td>141</td><td>118</td><td>151</td></tr><tr><td>2 CS Bn REME</td><td>263</td><td>108</td><td>53</td><td>91</td></tr><tr><td>110 Pro Coy</td><td>138</td><td>38</td><td>30</td><td>35</td></tr><tr><td>Total</td><td>805</td><td>287</td><td>201</td><td>277</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Dependents data is subject to change due to inflow and outflow of personnel to and from the units and has been estimated for planning purposes. <br><br>Fife Education Authority has visited the units in Germany and are in regular contact with officials regarding the number of children relocating to RAF Leuchars.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-07-02T15:30:33.3413035Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63602/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63602/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","RAF Leuchars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the (a) Royal Scots Dragoon Guards, (b) 2 Close Support Battalion REME and (c) 110 Provost Company RMP are scheduled to move to Leuchars; how many military personnel make up each unit; and how many (i) spouses and (ii) school-age children are attached to each unit.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","North East Fife","Sir Menzies Campbell","202097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63603","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-22","<p>By the end of financial year 2013-14, approximately £17 million had been spent on Typhoon-related works at Lossiemouth. The estimated capital costs for facilitating Typhoon Force-related operations, including the Northern Quick Reaction Alert facility, at RAF Lossiemouth is anticipated to be some £87 million.<br><br>The Basing Review, which was announced in July 2011, assessed what was best for Defence as a whole. This followed the Strategic Defence and Security Review in 2010, which stated the RAF needed three not four RAF fast jet bases.<br><br>The decisions made regarding RAF Leuchars and RAF Lossiemouth were also necessary to establish a coherent plan for basing the Army following its return from Germany and the opportunity to realise receipts by disposing of high value estate, while ensuring the build-up of the Typhoon force.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-07-22T15:23:57.8859729Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63603/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63603/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63603/answer/previousversion/7755","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","RAF Lossiemouth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost has been to date of all Typhoon Force-related capital works at RAF Lossiemouth; and what estimate he has made of the total cost of facilitating the future operation of the Typhoon Force and the Northern Quick Reaction Alert facility at that base.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","North East Fife","Sir Menzies Campbell","202098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63604","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The Commonwealth War Graves Commission ensures that the 1.7 million people who died in the two world wars will never be forgotten. The Commission cares for cemeteries and memorials at 23,000 locations, in 153 countries. It is therefore not possible to list every cemetery in this answer. Detailed and searchable information on the numbers of graves at each location in every relevant country is available on the Commission's website: http://www.cwgc.org/</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","202191","2014-07-02T15:33:16.7987212Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63604/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63604/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","War Graves","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many graves are maintained by the Commonwealth War Graves Commission, by (a) cemetery and (b) country.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63605","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The Commonwealth War Graves Commission ensures that the 1.7 million people who died in the two world wars will never be forgotten. The Commission cares for cemeteries and memorials at 23,000 locations, in 153 countries. It is therefore not possible to list every cemetery in this answer. Detailed and searchable information on the numbers of graves at each location in every relevant country is available on the Commission's website: http://www.cwgc.org/</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","202190","2014-07-02T15:33:16.876927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63605/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63605/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","War Graves","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which cemeteries are maintained by the Commonwealth War Graves Commission, by country; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Mr David Amess","202191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63606","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-06-30","<p>I responded to the hon. Member today.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","199311","2014-06-30T13:41:09.1927801Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63606/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63606/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63606/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he plans to respond to the letter of 5 May 2014 from the hon. Member for Cardiff South and Penarth on British Army processes of justice and requesting an urgent meeting.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","202085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63607","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-03","<p> </p><p>The principal transfer of Typhoon Force mission-specific equipment has been accomplished as part of an agreed change to an existing contract, at an additional cost of some £2.5 million.</p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-07-03T14:02:56.9007343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63607/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63607/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63607/answer/previousversion/7752","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","RAF Lossiemouth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost has been of transfer of all Typhoon Force mission-specific equipment and related removable fittings and fixtures from RAF Leuchars to RAF Lossiemouth; and what estimate has been made of the total cost of the transfer.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","North East Fife","Sir Menzies Campbell","202099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63608","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-22","<p>No Typhoon mission-specific infrastructure at RAF Leuchars has been identified for deconstruction, nor is it likely to be.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-07-22T15:29:02.959808Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63608/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63608/answer","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63608/answer/previousversion/7754","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","RAF Lossiemouth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what Typhoon Force mission-specific infrastructure at RAF Leuchars has been identified for deconstruction as a result of the transfer of the transfer of the Typhoon Force to RAF Lossiemouth.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","North East Fife","Sir Menzies Campbell","202100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63609","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-02","<p> </p><p>It is expected that over £5 million of investment will be made at RAF Leuchars to prepare for the arrival of Army units. This work is in the final stages of planning, we hope to begin the work soon.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2014-07-02T15:43:04.2063668Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63609/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63609/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","RAF Leuchars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what items of infrastructure have been (a) commissioned for installation and (b) installed at RAF Leuchars in preparation for the arrival of Army units and associated personnel; and how much each such item (i) is estimated to and (ii) has cost.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","North East Fife","Sir Menzies Campbell","202101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63610","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-01","<p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Defence has not had any discussions with his Egyptian counterpart on training and capacity building in the Egyptian army.<br><br>As part of wider UK defence engagement Ministry of Defence officials regularly discuss the potential for further engagement with a number of countries and may from time to time provide training as required and in accordance with wider Government policy.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2014-07-01T14:08:51.5830525Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63610/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63610/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-06-24","Egypt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with his Egyptian counterpart on training and capacity building in the Egyptian army.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","202265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63611","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-06-30","<p>The Government has made the Rock Enrol learning resource freely available on the Gov.UK and Times Education Supplement website amongst others.</p><p>Additionally, the recent introduction of online registration in England and Wales will make it more convenient for young people to register to vote.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-06-30T16:24:21.323761Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63611/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63611/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-06-24","Electoral Register: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, with reference to the Answer of 1 April 2014, Official Report, columns 555-6W, on electoral register, Northern Ireland, what actions resulted from his discussions with the Minister of State at the Northern Ireland Office concerning the schools programme for electoral registration.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","202243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63612","Deputy Prime Minister","false","2014-06-30","<p>The Government is supportive of organisations that promote democratic engagement such as Bite the Ballot.</p><p>Cabinet Office and Bite the Ballot co-developed the Rock Enrol learning resource in 2012/2013. The value of the contract was £25,700. The Government has made Rock Enrol freely available freely available on the gov.uk and Times Education Supplement websites.</p><p> </p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2014-06-30T16:23:26.3853485Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63612/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63612/answer",,,,,"58","Deputy Prime Minister","Deputy Prime Minister","2014-06-24","Electoral Register: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Deputy Prime Minister, with reference to the Answer of 28 January 2014, Official Report, column 510W, on electoral register: young people, how much funding his Department has made available to (a) Rock Enroll and (b) Bite the Ballot in each year for which data is available; and how many people each such organisation has directly registered in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","202035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63613","Department for Education","false","2014-07-07","<p>The information requested is set out in the table below.</p><p>Table 1: 2013-14 Performance Management Outturn Figures for the Department for Education</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Performance Rating</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Declared Disability</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No declared disability</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Not declared</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Top/Exceeded</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td><td><p>26%</p></td><td><p>22%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Achieving/Achieved</p></td><td><p>69%</p></td><td><p>66%</p></td><td><p>68%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Low/Must Improve</p></td><td><p>17%</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The Department continues to take steps to ensure that its performance ratings are a fair reflection of individual performance. Over the last year, this has included independent members being present at end of year meetings where performance assessments are moderated and training for staff on how to avoid unconscious bias.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-07T14:41:56.9154283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63613/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63613/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of (a) disabled and (b) all other staff employed by his Department received each level of performance rating in their end of year performance assessment for 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","202053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63614","Department for Education","false","2014-06-30","<p>Provisional figures on the number of trainees and proportion with a first or second class honours degree by subject are published in the Initial Teacher Training (ITT) Census in November each year. Finalised figures are published the following year. Provisional figures for 2013-14 are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-trainee-number-census-2013-to-2014/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-trainee-number-census-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-trainee-number-census-2013-to-2014</a></p><p> </p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-30T14:44:22.4686974Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63614/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63614/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teacher training bursaries for (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15 have been allocated to high-priority subjects of physics and mathematics at each of the four bursary tiers.","false","Biography information for Mark Reckless","Rochester and Strood","Mark Reckless","202240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63615","Department for Education","false","2014-06-30","<p>When community schools convert to academies, the freehold is retained by the local authority and a lease is granted to the academy trust.</p><p> </p><p>We have no plans to compensate local authorities in relation to the transfer of leasehold title to academy trusts as the land in question will continue being used for its original purpose: the education of children in high-quality local schools. In addition, there are strict rules protecting publicly funded land used by academies, regardless of who holds the freehold. This is set out in guidance published online at:</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/protection-of-school-playing-fields-and-public-land-advice" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/protection-of-school-playing-fields-and-public-land-advice</a></p><p> </p><p>A copy of the guidance has been placed in the House Library.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-06-30T16:40:14.7927608Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63615/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63615/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Academies: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will make it his policy to compensate local authorities whose leasehold title to land is transferred to academy trusts when the associated school achieves academy status.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","202246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63616","Department for Education","false","2014-06-30","<p>Sure Start children's centres statutory guidance was published in April 2013; the web page containing it was last reviewed on 25 March 2014.</p><p>The statutory guidance states the core purpose of Sure Start children's centres is to improve outcomes for young children and their families, with a particular focus on those in greatest need. The Department extensively consulted on draft statutory guidance, including the core purpose, in 2012. The response was positive, with 85% of respondees (local authorities, children's centre managers, voluntary sector bodies and others) finding the document clear on statutory duties.</p><p>As I said to the Education Committee on 18 June, Ofsted is going to be moving to a local-authority-based inspection regime for children's centres and I am very happy to look at the core purpose, particularly in the light of what Ofsted put out as their inspection regime, if there is a lack of clarity.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-06-30T15:35:55.98841Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63616/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63616/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Children's Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the guidance published by his Department on 25 March 2014, on Sure Start centres: local authority duties, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the core purpose of Sure Start children's centres.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","202251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63617","Department for Education","false","2014-06-30","<p>Information in relation to 2013-14 is not held in the form requested and could be compiled only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Data on 2014-15 participants has not yet been collected.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-30T14:53:46.8866197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63617/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63617/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Mathematics: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many of the graduates receiving bursaries to teach mathematics in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15 at each of the four tiers had (i) a mathematics degree, (ii) a relevant degree as defined by the School Workforce Survey and (iii) any other degree.","false","Biography information for Mark Reckless","Rochester and Strood","Mark Reckless","202238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63618","Department for Education","false","2014-06-30","<p>We initially allocated 15,254 places to School Direct and 23,095 places to higher education institutions for the 2014/15 academic year.</p><p>Further details of the initial allocations have been published on the gov.uk website:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-allocations-for-academic-year-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/initial-teacher-training-allocations-for-academic-year-2014-to-2015</a></p><p>We will publish final allocation information reflecting any changes later this year.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-30T14:39:47.5418422Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63618/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63618/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many places for initial teacher training starting in 2014 have been allocated to (a) Schools Direct and (b) higher education providers.","false","Biography information for Mark Reckless","Rochester and Strood","Mark Reckless","202239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63619","Department for Education","false","2014-06-30","<p>State-funded schools, including free schools and academies, should not teach creationism as an evidence-based scientific theory. Outside of science lessons, it is permissible for schools to cover creationism as part of religious education lessons, providing that this does not undermine the teaching of established scientific theory. Academies and free schools are required to teach a broad and balanced curriculum and the model funding agreement now prohibits the teaching of creationism as an evidence-based theory. Independent schools must comply with the independent school standards, and are subject to inspections by Ofsted or an alternative inspectorate.</p><p> </p><p>All state-funded schools are subject to Ofsted inspections and a range of intervention powers are in place if required. In addition, any breach of academy or free school funding agreements in relation to creationism would be swiftly dealt with by the Department for Education and could result in the termination of the funding agreement.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-06-30T16:37:29.5826667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63619/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63619/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Creationism: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what penalties would be incurred by a free school, academy or other educational establishment which was found to be teaching or otherwise supporting creationism.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","202221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63620","Department for Education","false","2014-07-01","<p>The Department and agencies have no current contracts with the educational testing service or its subsidiaries.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2014-07-01T13:26:07.987007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63620/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63620/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Educational Testing Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what current contracts (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's executive agencies or non-departmental public bodies hold with the educational testing service or any of that organisation's subsidiaries.","false","Biography information for Nick Gibb","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","202233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63621","Department for Education","false","2014-07-01","<p>The way in which specialist support is provided will vary according to local arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>When specialist provision is required, schools and teachers should have support from appropriately trained and qualified local health partners and other organisations. Both education and health providers should be clear when referrals to Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services (CAMHS) are the most appropriate form of specialist support.</p><p> </p><p>To support schools with doing this, on 16 June 2014 the Department for Education issued new non-statutory guidance for schools and teachers on pupils' mental health and behaviour. This guidance helps school staff identify those pupils who may have emerging problems and provides guidance on appropriate routes of ensuring appropriate specialist support where necessary.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-07-01T16:27:25.2686847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63621/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63621/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Pupils: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of specialist support within maintained schools to help students with mental health problems.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","202247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63622","Department for Education","false","2014-06-30","<p>Information in relation to 2013-14 is not held in the form requested and could be compiled only at disproportionate cost.</p><p>Data on 2014-15 participants has not yet been collected.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-30T14:38:27.7722729Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63622/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63622/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Physics: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many of the graduates receiving bursaries to teach physics in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15 at each of the four tiers had (i) a physics degree, (ii) a relevant degree in respect of physics as defined by the School Workforce Survey and (iii) any other degree.","false","Biography information for Mark Reckless","Rochester and Strood","Mark Reckless","202237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63623","Department for Education","false","2014-06-30","<p>Since January 2014, we have allocated subject knowledge enhancement (SKE) places to 110 schools, supporting 151 applicants to commence their initial teacher training. One applicant relates to entry into initial teacher training (ITT) in 2013/14 and 150 relate to entry in 2014/15. We did not collect data on SKE courses requested by School Direct schools before January 2014. Because SKE can be delivered in parallel with ITT, the trainee does not necessarily have to complete SKE prior to starting ITT.</p><p>A full breakdown of SKE course data by subject will be available from October 2014.</p>","Yeovil","Mr David Laws",,"2014-06-30T14:46:02.0354469Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63623/answer","Biography information for Mr David Laws","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63623/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-06-24","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many School Direct initial teacher training offers in (a) 2013-14 and 2014-15 in each subject area were made conditional on completion of a subject knowledge enhancement programme.","false","Biography information for Mark Reckless","Rochester and Strood","Mark Reckless","202236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63624","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-02","<p>The secondary legislation for the Electricity Market Reform programme contains provisions to move straight to allocation rounds, with competitive auctions setting the price where the demand for CfDs exceeds the available budget.</p><p>DECC analysis shows that the pipeline of projects is strong and can deliver a competitive outcome, whilst the Administrative Strike Price sets a cap to protect consumers.</p><p>More generally, the auction has been designed to encourage participation, and we are introducing the Offtaker of Last Resort (OLR) to support independent renewable generators by providing them with a guaranteed route to market and improving their ability to raise project finance.</p><p>DECC officials have worked closely with developers and other stakeholders on these proposals, and the approach to implementing the OLR is currently being consulted on.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-07-02T15:44:27.7837771Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63624/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63624/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Answer of 14 May 2014, Official Report, column 595W, on electricity, what assessment he has made of whether the ability of auctions to drive value for money is dependent on market plurality and competition; and if he will make it a formal objective of his Department to ensure that independent generators are able to compete in Contracts for Difference auctions on an equal footing.","false","Biography information for Dan Byles","North Warwickshire","Dan Byles","202195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63625","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-26","<p>There are currently no employees, seconded from any of the big six energy companies, working in the Department of Energy &amp; Climate Change.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-06-26T15:06:10.5533784Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63625/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63625/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many employees of the big six energy companies are currently seconded to his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","202242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63626","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-01","<p>The UK Government engages with Egypt on a series of renewable technologies, including solar, through multilateral forms such at the International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA). We also provide some technical assistance, through the World Bank, to help Egypt diversify their energy sources.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-01T14:35:08.0142562Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63626/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63626/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Renewable Energy: Egypt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if he will discuss (a) solar energy and (b) other alternative energies with his Egyptian counterpart.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","202268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63627","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-30","<p>Recent changes in the estimated costs of dealing with legacy radioactive waste and decommissioning announced in the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority's Annual Report and Accounts for 2013/14 are due in their entirety to the decommissioning programme at Sellafield. These costs should not be used as a guide to costs of decommissioning modern nuclear reactor sites. The vast majority of the liability at Sellafield is a result of the Cold War military programme on that site, dating back to the 1940s, and the very early days of the civil nuclear industry, dating back to the 1950s and 1960s. These historic facilities were built extremely rapidly to very different quality and safety standards compared with nuclear plants constructed today and without plans for how they would be ultimately decommissioned, These facilities present a unique decommissioning challenge requiring a complex suite of engineering projects in order to first gain access to their waste inventory before retrieving and then treating this material ready for long-term disposal. The activity required to decommission these facilities at Sellafield bears no relation to the work required to decommission modern nuclear facilities. Operators of nuclear power stations being constructed under the Government's new build programme are required to publish plans detailing how these facilities will be decommissioned and the operators themselves are liable for the costs associated with this decommissioning work.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-06-30T15:17:04.7323262Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63627/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63627/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Nuclear Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority's Annual Report and Accounts for 2013-14, published on 23 June 2014, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policy on the evaluation of proposals for funded radioactive waste and decommissioning plans presented to him by private nuclear operators of the recent increase in the cost of dealing with legacy radioactive waste and decommissioning announced in that report.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","202280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63628","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-30","<p>The decision on contract extension was for the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority in line with its duties and responsibilities under the Energy Act 2004. The Department has oversight of all NDA activity and, given the particular importance of Sellafield, officials were closely involved throughout the contract review. From this we were assured that the NDA reached its decision based on a thorough and independent review of performance in the first period of the contract and consideration of all the options available to it. Ministers endorsed the NDA Board's decision to extend the contract for a second term on the basis that rolling the contract forward represented the best way forward, giving the opportunity for NMP to build on progress made to date, address weaker areas of performance and make further real progress in this next five year term.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-06-30T15:18:07.1635753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63628/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63628/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Sellafield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the evidential basis was for the statement made by his Department's Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State in her foreword to the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority's Annual Report and Accounts for 2013-14, issued on 23 June 2014, that the continuation of Nuclear Management Partner's contract to manage the Sellafield site offers the potential of stability and focus on the priorities during a vital five-year period in the history of Sellafield as it transitions from an operational plant into a fully-fledged decommissioning site.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","202281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63629","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-30","<p>As reported in the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority's Annual Report and Accounts for 2013/14, the Nuclear Provision (the estimated cost to complete the decommissioning of all 17 sites in the authority's estate) is now calculated as £65bn on a discounted basis (£110bn undiscounted). These costs will be borne in their entirety by the public purse.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-06-30T15:18:55.5026715Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63629/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63629/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Nuclear Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority's Annual Report and Accounts for 2013-14, published on 23 June 2014, what estimate he has made of the additional cost to the public purse arising from the increased cost on an undiscounted basis of legacy radioactive waste and nuclear plant commissioning announced in that report.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","202282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63630","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-01","<p>Applications made to the Green Deal Home Improvement Fund which comply with the scheme terms and conditions will typically be turned around and a voucher issued within 5 working days. Vouchers are redeemable once the customer has completed their installation of energy saving home improvements.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-01T14:35:48.5203539Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63630/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63630/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the average turnaround is on applications for funding under the Green Deal scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","202075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63631","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-30","<p> </p><p>In DECC the staff declaration rate for disability is:</p><ul><li>5.7% have declared they have a disability;</li><li>70.6% have declared they don't have a disability;</li><li>23.7% have not declared their disability status.</li></ul><p>The 2013/14 performance ratings breakdown for these groups is:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><em>Declared have a disability</em></p></td><td><p><em>Declared don't have a disability</em></p></td><td><p><em>Disability status not declared</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong><em>1- SCS, Top; AO-G6, Exceptional performance.</em></strong></p></td><td><p>12.2%</p></td><td><p>27.1%</p></td><td><p>22.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong><em>2 - SCS, Achieving; AO-G6, Effective performance.</em></strong></p></td><td><p>70.7%</p></td><td><p>67.5%</p></td><td><p>70.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong><em>3 – SCS, Low; AO-G6, Need for improvement/ developing</em></strong></p></td><td><p>17.1%</p></td><td><p>5.5%</p></td><td><p>6.8%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-06-30T14:17:31.258227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63631/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63631/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what proportion of (a) disabled and (b) all other staff employed by his Department received each level of performance rating in their end of year performance assessment for 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","202054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63632","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-30","<p>I met with the Independent Renewable Generators Group on 24th February 2014 and discussed the introduction of auctioning for Contracts for Difference (CfDs).</p><p>The Offtaker of Last Resort will support independent renewable generators by providing for the worst-case route-to-market, allowing generators to raise project finance without necessarily having to enter long-term PPAs. As a result, such generators are likely only to need short-term PPAs in order to maximise their secured revenue and level of gearing. We are on track to deliver the final policy and introduce enabling regulations ahead of first allocation of CfDs. CfD applicants will, therefore, have a high degree of clarity about the arrangements for OLR in advance of the first auctions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-06-30T15:16:11.1565996Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63632/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63632/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Electricity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Answer of 14 May 2014, Official Report, column 593W, on electricity, what recent discussions he has had with the Independent Renewables Generators Group on the timing of the introduction of auctioning; what assessment he has made of independent generators' ability to raise project finance against the Offtaker of Last Resort before October 2014; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dan Byles","North Warwickshire","Dan Byles","202094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63633","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-01","<p>Since the domestic Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) scheme launched on 9 April this year, up until the end of May, Ofgem had received 2,296 applications to join the scheme.</p><p>Whether or not an application meets the minimum insulation standard is determined using information from the Energy Performance Certificate of the property. Currently, Ofgem do not record data on applicants that are not eligible for the scheme due to not meeting minimum insulation standards, as this check precedes an applicant completing a full application.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-01T14:32:09.6513004Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63633/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63633/answer","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63633/answer/previousversion/6945","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment he has made of the number of domestic renewable heat incentive applications received since April 2014; and how many such applications have been turned down because they did not meet minimum insulation standards.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","202208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63634","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-07-01","<p>Since the domestic Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) launched on 9 April this year, up until the end of May Ofgem had received 2,296 applications in total from applicants in England, Wales and Scotland.</p><p>Due to the infancy of the scheme, analysis is not currently provided at country level, however this breakdown will be presented in our next monthly Renewable Heat Incentive and Renewable Heat Premium Payment statistics to be published on 24 July. These data will be available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/renewable-heat-incentive-renewable-heat-premium-payment-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/renewable-heat-incentive-renewable-heat-premium-payment-statistics</a></p><p>The Domestic RHI scheme is open only to those living in England, Scotland or Wales. Northern Ireland is planning to introduce its own equivalent scheme to support domestic renewable heat generation shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-07-01T14:34:16.503602Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63634/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63634/answer","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63634/answer/previousversion/6942","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate he has made of the number of Domestic Renewable Heat Incentive applications that have been received from (a) England, (b) Wales, (c) Scotland and (d) Northern Ireland since April 2014.","false","Biography information for Tom Greatrex","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Tom Greatrex","202205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63635","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-30","<p>Neither (a) The Department of Energy and Climate Change nor (b) its non-Departmental public bodies hold any contracts with the Educational Testing Service or its subsidiaries.</p><p> </p>","Bexhill and Battle","Gregory Barker",,"2014-06-30T14:18:16.2509482Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63635/answer","Biography information for Lord Barker of Battle","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63635/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2014-06-24","Educational Testing Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what current contracts (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's executive agencies or non-departmental public bodies hold with the Educational Testing Service or any of that organisation's subsidiaries.","false","Biography information for Nick Gibb","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Mr Nick Gibb","202168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63636","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2014-06-30","<p>The Electricity Market Reform (EMR) Delivery Plan published in December 2013 included an estimate for the total amount of available coal-fired electricity generation capacity in Great Britain in each year to 2030. It is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/268221/181213_2013_EMR_Delivery_Plan_FINAL.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/268221/181213_2013_EMR_Delivery_Plan_FINAL.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>See table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total coal-fired capacity (GW)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2014</em></p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2015</em></p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2016</em></p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2017</em></p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2018</em></p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2019</em></p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2020</em></p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2021</em></p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2022</em></p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2023</em></p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2024</em></p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2025</em></p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2026</em></p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2027</em></p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2028</em></p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2029</em></p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>2030</em></p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>* Based on a scenario of average carbon intensity of electricity generation of 100g CO<sub>2</sub>/kWh in 2030</em></p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2014-06-30T14:22:58.4518225Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/63636/answer","